The federal government through the Ministry of Works and Housing has handed over the 2 kilometer road rehabilitated and reconstructed to the Kaduna Polytechnic. The rehabilitation and reconstruction was part of the federal government’s intervention on rehabilitation of internal roads within tertiary institutions. At the handing over ceremony, the minister of Works and Housing, Babatunde Raji Fashola (SAN), said: “The gap of our infrastructure needs is steadily being bridged by gradual process of repairs, renewal and construction on major highways and it has reached the schools”. Represented by the Federal Controller Works, Kaduna,  Finbarr Zirra James, the minister disclosed that currently there are 43 such interventions in internal roads within tertiary institutions across Nigeria which has brought about renewed enthusiasm on the part of students with regards to attending classes following the motorability of the roads. “To date, 18 out of the 43 interventions have been completed and today we are handing over this one in Kaduna Polytechnic, Kaduna State as critical contribution to support education,” he said. The minister informed that during the construction, 25 people were employed in the process contributing to the job creation initiatives of the government. In an overview of the project, director of Works, Kaduna Polytechnic, Engr. Ummu Aminu, said details of the works carried out include scarification of the existing bituminous surfacing, filing of potholes, construction of reinforced concrete lined drains, provision and laying of 100mm thick interlocks as walkway and provision and laying of asphaltic concrete wearing course among others. In his address earlier, the rector of the polytechnic, Prof. Idris Mohammed Bugaje commended the federal government for the intervention and requested that the intervention be further extended to other campuses whose roads are in dire need of rehabilitation.